<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> See, for instance, the 2000 ruling of the <i><a href="/wiki/Conseil_d%27%C3%89tat" title="Conseil d'État" class="mw-redirect">Conseil d'État</a></i>, <i><a href="http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/WAspad/UnTexteDeJorf?numjo=CETX0004174V" class="external text" title="http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/WAspad/UnTexteDeJorf?numjo=CETX0004174V" rel="nofollow">Mlle Marteaux</a></i>).</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.conseil-etat.fr/ce/missio/index_mi_cg03_01.shtml" class="external text" title="http://www.conseil-etat.fr/ce/missio/index_mi_cg03_01.shtml" rel="nofollow">"Official website of the Conseil d'État"</a>. Conseil-etat.fr<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.conseil-etat.fr/ce/missio/index_mi_cg03_01.shtml" class="external free" title="http://www.conseil-etat.fr/ce/missio/index_mi_cg03_01.shtml" rel="nofollow">http://www.conseil-etat.fr/ce/missio/index_mi_cg03_01.shtml</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2009-01-31</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Official+website+of+the+Conseil+d%27%C3%89tat&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.pub=Conseil-etat.fr&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.conseil-etat.fr%2Fce%2Fmissio%2Findex_mi_cg03_01.shtml&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:French_law_on_secularity_and_conspicuous_religious_symbols_in_schools"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> Because Islam is not a hierarchical religion in the way that Roman Catholicism is (the only hierarchical structure being the currently-defunct <a href="/wiki/Caliphate" title="Caliphate">Caliphate</a>), it is not obvious which religious representatives should be engaged in discussion by public powers. In addition, contrary to other religious tendencies such as <a href="/wiki/Protestant" title="Protestant" class="mw-redirect">Protestantism</a>, Islam did not have an umbrella organisation in France. To remedy this last issue, in 2003 <a href="/wiki/Nicolas_Sarkozy" title="Nicolas Sarkozy">Nicolas Sarkozy</a>, then <a href="/wiki/Minister_of_the_Interior_(France)" title="Minister of the Interior (France)">Minister of the Interior</a>, set up the <a href="/wiki/French_Council_of_the_Muslim_Faith" title="French Council of the Muslim Faith">French Council of the Muslim Faith</a>, which the State uses as a discussion partner for such issues. This council, however, is merely a private non-profit association and has no special legal standing, nor is it universally accepted as being representative of the opinions of Muslims residing in France.</li>
